What is iTJSDispatch2

　iTJSDispatch2 is an abstract base class that provides an interface to "objects" in TJS2.
　"Objects" of TJS2 include function objects, classes, property objects, and arrays (dictionary arrays).
　Most operations on TJS2 can be performed through this interface.

　In the following, it is described as the side using this interface.

Call by ordinal


　Some iTJSDispatch2 methods have method names that end with ByNum. This is a call by ordinal. For example, calling FuncCall with a member name of "23" is equivalent to calling FuncCallByNum with an ordinal of 23.
　Useful when accessing array objects.

　Methods ending with ByNum have no membername and hint arguments for methods of the same name without the suffix ByNum, but instead have tjs_int num. Specify an ordinal number in the argument num.

　In the following, the method that calls by ordinal is not described in detail (see the description of the method with the same name without ByNum at the end).

AddRef

tjs_uint iTJSDispatch2::AddRef(void)

　Increments the reference counter for the object.
　Each object of TJS2 is managed by reference counter.
　The return value is the value of the reference counter after the increment, but trusting this value is not recommended.

Release

tjs_uint iTJSDispatch2::Release(void)

　Decrements the object's reference counter.
　The return value is the value of the reference counter after decrementing. A return of 0 indicates that the object has been released. However, trusting this value is not recommended.

FuncCall

tjs_error iTJSDispatch2::FuncCall(
    tjs_uint32 flag,
    const tjs_char * membername,
    tjs_uint32 *hint,
    tTJSVariant *result,
    tjs_int numparams,
    tTJSVariant **param,
    iTJSDispatch2 *objthis
    )

　Make a function call.

　The arguments are as follows:

tjs_uint32 flag
　Call flag (see below).
const tjs_char * membername
　Member name to be operated.
　If NULL, the operation is on this object itself. In this case, this object must be able to function.
tjs_uint32 *hint
　"Hint" for variable storage. May be NULL.
　The hint is to speed up the search for the same member name from the second time. If you specify a pointer to a tjs_uint32 type variable for hint, the hint value is written to it. From the second time onward, search for members by referring to the numerical value. For hints, the initial value of the hint can be any value (0 is recommended). In addition, due to such a mechanism, it is more efficient if there is a one-to-one correspondence between hints and corresponding member names (tTJSString type has a mechanism for this hint).
　Some objects may not have a mechanism for using hints.
tTJSVariant *result
　Points to a tTJSVariant to store the result of calling the function.
　If no result is needed, NULL can be specified.
tjs_int numparams
　Specify the number of arguments to pass to the function.
tTJSVariant **param
　Pass an array of pointers to the arguments to pass to the function. May be NULL if there are no arguments.
iTJSDispatch2 *objthis
　Specifies the context (this object) in which the function runs.

tjs_error iTJSDispatch2::FuncCall(

    tTJSVariant *result,
    tjs_int numparams,
    tTJSVariant **param,
    iTJSDispatch2 *objthis
    )

　Makes a function call by ordinal.

PropGet

tjs_error iTJSDispatch2::PropGet(
    tjs_uint32 flag,
    const tjs_char * membername,
    tjs_uint32 *hint,
    tTJSVariant *result,
    iTJSDispatch2 *objthis
    )

　Gets the value of a property or member variable.

　The arguments are as follows:

tjs_uint32 flag
　Call flag (see below).
const tjs_char * membername
　Member name to be operated.

　If NULL, the operation is on this object itself. In this case, this object must be able to get properties.
　Objects that succeed even if this argument is NULL are considered property objects. Normally, when such a property object becomes a member of another object, the result of performing PropGet on that property object is used instead of this property object itself. This behavior can be bypassed by specifying TJS_IGNOREPROP in the call flag.
tjs_uint32 *hint
　Specify the area of the variable to store the hint. May be NULL.
　See the description of FuncCall for a description of the hint.
tTJSVariant *result
　Pointer to the tTJSVariant type to store the result. NULL is not allowed.
iTJSDispatch2 *objthis
　Specifies the context (this object) in which this method runs.

    iTJSDispatch2 *objthis
    )

PropSetByVS

tjs_error iTJSDispatch2::PropSetByVS(
    tjs_uint32 flag,
    tTJSVariantString *membername,
    const tTJSVariant *param,
    iTJSDispatch2 *objthis
    )

　Set the values of properties and member variables. Unlike PropSet, member names are referenced by tTJSVariantString. Used internally. Since tTJSVariantString has the same string memory area shared by multiple string objects, setting properties (creating a member in the object) through this method will result in a member name It can prevent the increase of the memory for the character string memory area used for.
　If you do not implement this method, return TJS_E_NOTIMPL. PropSet is used instead. Also, if this method returns TJS_E_NOTIMPL, implement PropSet instead.

　See the description of FuncCall for a description of the hint.
iTJSDispatch2 *objthis

　This argument is usually meaningless (ignored).

EnumMembers

tjs_error iTJSDispatch2::EnumMembers(
        tjs_uint32 flag,
        tTJSVariantClosure *callback,
        iTJSDispatch2 *objthis
        )

　Enumerates members in an object.
　A callback function can be specified for callback, but in the current version, the operation when creating or deleting a member of this object in the callback function is not guaranteed.

　The arguments are as follows:
　
tjs_uint32 flag
　Call flag. For the call flag, specify the bit OR of the following flags or 0 (zero).
TJS_IGNOREPROP
　Disable property access. When enumerating members and obtaining values, if this flag is specified, if the member is a property, the property object itself will be obtained. If you do not specify this flag, you get the value obtained through the property object.
TJS_ENUM_NO_VALUE
　Do not get the value. If this flag is specified, two arguments will be passed to the callback function. If specified, there will be three.
tTJSVariantClosure *callback
　Specify a callback function.
　In this callback function, callback-> FuncCall is called once for each member.
　Two (if TJS_ENUM_NO_VALUE is specified) or three (if TJS_ENUM_NO_VALUE is not specified) arguments are passed to the function.
  • The first argument is a string type and is a member name
  • The second argument is of type integer and is a flag for its members. Combination of bitwise OR of TJS_HIDDENMEMBER or TJS_STATICMEMBER, or 0 is specified
  • The third argument exists only when TJS_ENUM_NO_VALUE is not specified, and indicates the value of the member
iTJSDispatch2 *objthis
　Specifies the context (this object) in which this method runs.
　This argument is the default context in which the property object will run if the TJS_IGNOREPROP flag is not specified.

    tjs_int numparams,
    tTJSVariant **param,
    iTJSDispatch2 *objthis
    )

　Create a new object.
　This method is similar to the FuncCall method and allows you to pass arguments to create a new object.
　The so-called "class object", which is the model of the object, must implement this method.

　The arguments are as follows:

tjs_uint32 flag
　Call flag (see below).
const tjs_char * membername
　Member name to be operated.
　If NULL, the operation is on this object itself. In this case, this object must have the ability to create a new object.
tjs_uint32 *hint
　Specify the area of the variable to store the hint. May be NULL.
　See the description of FuncCall for a description of the hint.
iTJSDispatch2 **result
　Pointer to the iTJSDispatch * type to store the newly created object. NULL is not allowed.
tjs_int numparams
　Specify the number of arguments to pass when creating a new object.
tTJSVariant **param
　Pass an array of pointers of arguments to pass when creating a new object. May be NULL if there are no arguments.
iTJSDispatch2 *objthis
　Specify the context (this object) to be executed when creating a new object.

Operation

tjs_error iTJSDispatch2::Operation(
    tjs_uint32 flag,
    const tjs_char *membername,
    tjs_uint32 *hint,
    tTJSVariant *result,
    const tTJSVariant *param,
    iTJSDispatch2 *objthis
    )

　Performs operations on members. The type of operation is specified by flag.

　The arguments are as follows:

tjs_uint32 flag
　Call flag. In addition to the following normal call flags, one of the following flags must be added with a bit OR to specify the type of operation.

　In this description, v represents the member value, and p represents the parameter passed in the param argument.

TJS_OP_BAND
Bit AND operation
v &= p
TJS_OP_BOR
Bit OR operation
v |= p
TJS_OP_BXOR
Bit XOR operation
v ^= p
TJS_OP_SUB
Subtraction
v -= p
TJS_OP_ADD
Addition
v += p
TJS_OP_MOD
Modulus
v %= p
TJS_OP_DIV
Real number division
v /= p
TJS_OP_IDIV
Integer division
v \= p
TJS_OP_MUL
Multiplication
v *= p
TJS_OP_LOR
Logical OR
v = v || p
TJS_OP_LAND
Logical AND
v = v && p
TJS_OP_SAR
Arithmetic right shift
v >>= p
TJS_OP_SAL
Arithmetic left shift
v <<= p
TJS_OP_SR
Bit shift right
v >>>= p
TJS_OP_INC
Increment
v++
param argument ignored
TJS_OP_DEC
Decrement
v--
param argument ignored
const tjs_char * membername
　Member name to be operated. NULL is not allowed.
tjs_uint32 *hint
　Specify the area of the variable to store the hint. May be NULL.
　See the description of FuncCall for a description of the hint.
tTJSVariant *result
　Pointer to a variable of type tTJSVariant to store the result of the operation. Can be NULL.
tTJSVariant *param
　Specify the parameters for the operation. If TJS_OP_INC or TJS_OP_DEC is specified for the operation type, it can be NULL.
iTJSDispatch2 *objthis
　Specifies the context in which the operation is performed, but is usually ignored.

NativeInstanceSupport

tjs_error iTJSDispatch2::NativeInstanceSupport(
    tjs_uint32 flag,
    tjs_int32 classid,
    iTJSNativeInstance **pointer
    )

　Associate an instance of native code with an object or get an instance of native code from an object.

　The arguments are as follows:

tjs_uint32 flag
　Specifies the call flags.
　You must specify one of the following values:

TJS_NIS_REGISTER
　Register the instance of the native code indicated by *pointer. Use classid to identify the class of native code.
TJS_NIS_GETINSTANCE
　Write an instance of native code with the class ID specified by classid to *pointer.
tjs_int32 classid
　Specify the native code class ID.
　TJSRegisterNativeClass for managing native code class IDs TJSFindNativeClassID You can use TJSFindNativeClassName, but usually these processes are automatically handled by the supporting code group for writing native code (described in tjsNative.cpp / tjsNative.h).
iTJSNativeInstance **pointer
　Specifies a pointer to a variable of type iTJSNativeInstance * to pass or receive an instance of native code.

ClassInstanceInfo

tjs_error iTJSDispatch2::ClassInstanceInfo(
    tjs_uint32 flag,
    tjs_uint num,
    tTJSVariant *value
    )

　A method that operates on the instance information of the class used in the IsInstanceOf method.
　You can add a class name to identify which class the object is an instance of, or enumerate the classes to find out which class the object is an instance of.

　The arguments are as follows:

tjs_uint32 flag
　Call flag. Specify one of the following flags:

TJS_CII_ADD
　Add instance information.
　In value, pass a pointer to a tTJSVariant type variable that stores the class name (string).
　The num argument is ignored.
TJS_CII_GET
　Get instance information.
　Specify an integer starting from 0 for the num argument. TJS_E_FAIL is returned if num is specified exceeding the number of set instance information.
　In value, pass a pointer to a tTJSVariant type variable to receive the class name.
tjs_uint num
　Specify the ordinal number when TJS_CII_GET is specified for flag.
tTJSVariant *value
　If TJS_CII_ADD is specified for flag, pass a pointer to a tTJSVariant variable that stores the class name.
　If TJS_CII_GET is specified for flag, pass a pointer to a tTJSVariant type variable to receive the class name.

Call flag

　Call flag.
　You can specify combinations of the following values by bit OR.

TJS_MEMBERENSURE
　If the specified member name is not found, force the member to be created. Valid as a call flag to PropSet.
TJS_MEMBERMUSTEXIST
　Generates an error if the specified member name is not found. This is useful for objects such as Dictionary and Array that return void by default if a member is not found (otherwise an error will occur by default if the member is not found) ).
TJS_IGNOREPROP
　Bypass property operations.
　A TJS2 object normally returns the result of PropSet or PropGet for that member as a substitute for that member if the specified member is an object and PropSet or PropGet succeeds on that object (if it is a property object). I will use it.
　When this flag is specified, such processing is bypassed, so even if the specified member is a property object, the operation is performed on the property object itself.
TJS_HIDDENMEMBER
　Creating a member with this flag makes the member invisible. Some objects may not be supported.
TJS_STATICMEMBER
　When a member is created with this flag, the member is static (independent of the execution context). Some objects may not be supported.

tjs_error

　tjs_error is the error type returned by each method of iTJSDispatch2 (except AddRef and Release).
　Takes the following values. Also, even if the value is not listed here, if the value is negative, it must be regarded as an error. You can use the TJS_SUCCEEDED and TJS_FAILED macros to determine these.

TJS_E_MEMBERNOTFOUND
　The specified member cannot be found.
TJS_E_NOTIMPL
　The function you attempted to call has not been implemented.
TJS_E_INVALIDPARAM
　Invalid argument.
TJS_E_BADPARAMCOUNT
　The number of arguments is invalid.
TJS_E_INVALIDTYPE
　It is not a function or the property type is different.
　This value is returned when you try to call a non-function object or treat a non-property object as a property.
TJS_E_INVALIDOBJECT
　The object has already been invalidated.
TJS_E_ACCESSDENYED
　You attempted an operation that cannot be performed on a read or write-only property.
TJS_E_NATIVECLASSCRASH
　The execution context is different.
　This value is returned when an attempt is made to execute a method implemented in native code in a context that cannot be handled by the native code (such as on an object of a different class).
TJS_S_TRUE
　Not an error, but indicates that the result is true.
TJS_S_FALSE
　Not an error, but indicates that the result is false.
TJS_S_OK
　This value usually returns if no error occurred.
TJS_E_FAIL
　This value is returned if an undefined error occurs.
TJS_FAILED(x)
　A macro that will be true if x is an error value.
TJS_SUCCEEDED(x)
　A macro that is true if x is a non-error value.


　Error definitions and related macros are found in tjsErrorDef.h.
　Also, a runtime exception (in C++) may be thrown instead of an error. When it comes to programming, you need to consider run-time exceptions.
